  "prompt": "Why wasn't John Williams hired to write the soundtrack to Rogue One?",
  "response": "John Williams, the legendary composer known for his iconic scores for the Star Wars saga, was not hired to write the soundtrack for *Rogue One: A Star Wars Story* (2016) primarily because the film was intended to have a distinct musical identity separate from the main episodic films. Williams had already committed to composing the scores for *The Force Awakens* (2015) and *The Last Jedi* (2017), and the filmmakers wanted a fresh take for the standalone anthology film.\n\nInstead, **Michael Giacchino** was chosen to compose the score for *Rogue One*. Giacchino is a highly respected composer known for his work on films like *Up*, *Jurassic World*, and many others. His score for *Rogue One* incorporated some of Williams' original themes (such as the Star Wars main title and the Force theme) but also introduced new musical elements to reflect the film's grittier, war-focused tone.\n\nThe decision to hire a different composer for *Rogue One* aligns with Disney and Lucasfilm's strategy to differentiate the anthology films from the main saga, both in tone and musical style. This approach allowed Giacchino to create a unique sound while still paying homage to Williams' legacy.",
